00:02:25.700 --> 00:02:27.550
It didn't really
make me that happy.

00:02:27.550 --> 00:02:28.550
So I thought, all right.

00:02:28.550 --> 00:02:29.050
I know.

00:02:29.050 --> 00:02:30.680
I know know.

00:02:30.680 --> 00:02:33.010
I'll be happy when I
get into Vanderbilt.

00:02:33.010 --> 00:02:36.040
So I got into Vanderbilt.
Freshman year came,

00:02:36.040 --> 00:02:39.470
and the happiness
highs subsided.

00:02:39.470 --> 00:02:42.980
I thought, OK, getting
ready for adult world.

00:02:42.980 --> 00:02:45.260
I'll be happy when I
get a high-paying job.

00:02:45.260 --> 00:02:47.970
So I got the high paying IT job.

00:02:47.970 --> 00:02:52.300
And a year into my work,
I was sitting at my desk

00:02:52.300 --> 00:02:55.590
still not feeling very
happy or fulfilled.

00:02:55.590 --> 00:02:57.450
And I was running out of ideas.

00:02:57.450 --> 00:02:58.450
I started brainstorming.

00:02:58.450 --> 00:02:59.830
What's at the end
of the sentence.

00:02:59.830 --> 00:03:00.663
I'll be happy when--

00:03:00.663 --> 00:03:02.350
I'll be happy when.

00:03:02.350 --> 00:03:04.410
I finally figured it out.

00:03:04.410 --> 00:03:08.710
I thought I'll be happy
when I have a fast car,

00:03:08.710 --> 00:03:10.780
make six figures, and have
a girlfriend who plays

00:03:10.780 --> 00:03:14.230
Super Smash Bros. with me--

00:03:14.230 --> 00:03:16.690
and a six pack.

00:03:16.690 --> 00:03:22.460
I got most of those, and
I still wasn't happy.

00:03:22.460 --> 00:03:24.760
And then I started to
feel a little desperate.

00:03:24.760 --> 00:03:26.560
I was running out of ideas.

00:03:26.560 --> 00:03:30.400
So I settled on the
idea that I'll be happy

00:03:30.400 --> 00:03:34.346
when I make enough money.

00:03:34.346 --> 00:03:36.580
Well, I made enough money.

00:03:36.580 --> 00:03:39.530
It still didn't work.

00:03:39.530 --> 00:03:42.370
And one day, I was sitting
at my desk at work,

00:03:42.370 --> 00:03:46.330
and I got the email from
my mom that was addressed

00:03:46.330 --> 00:03:48.770
to me, Chris, and Greg.

00:03:48.770 --> 00:03:51.810
Well, Chris and Greg are
also my uncles' names.

00:03:51.810 --> 00:03:55.600
And the email said, let's
not tell the grandkids yet,

00:03:55.600 --> 00:03:58.520
but dad's dying.

00:03:58.520 --> 00:04:01.750
And in response to the news that
my grandfather, my childhood

00:04:01.750 --> 00:04:05.500
hero, was dying when I thought
he was in perfect health,

00:04:05.500 --> 00:04:07.640
I felt absolutely nothing.

00:04:07.640 --> 00:04:10.570
And that's when I knew
something was seriously wrong.

00:04:10.570 --> 00:04:16.940
So I went to check in to talk
to a therapist, my mental health

00:04:16.940 --> 00:04:18.890
squad, as I called him.

00:04:18.890 --> 00:04:21.760
And eventually, I was
prescribed some antidepressants

00:04:21.760 --> 00:04:24.490
shortly after being
told I was depressed.

00:04:24.490 --> 00:04:27.730
And these pills helped me
go from negative 5 to 0.

00:04:27.730 --> 00:04:30.380
And I thought, that's
not good enough.

00:04:30.380 --> 00:04:31.930
That's not good
enough for me, that's

00:04:31.930 --> 00:04:34.380
not good enough for
every young person who's

00:04:34.380 --> 00:04:35.800
been in this situation--

00:04:35.800 --> 00:04:38.050
wondering what
happiness is, wondering

00:04:38.050 --> 00:04:40.480
how to treat stress,
anxiety, and depression,

00:04:40.480 --> 00:04:44.290
going from negative 5
to 0 isn't good enough.

00:04:44.290 --> 00:04:47.498
How do we go from 0 to 10?

00:04:47.498 --> 00:04:49.540
And that question has been
driving me ever since.

00:04:49.540 --> 00:04:51.950
That was about four years ago.

00:04:51.950 --> 00:04:56.170
So at that point, I had
a crossroads in my life.

00:04:56.170 --> 00:04:59.506
I had a promotion
offer on my desk.

00:04:59.506 --> 00:05:02.200
But I thought I can
help the world more if I

00:05:02.200 --> 00:05:05.110
tried to answer this question.

00:05:05.110 --> 00:05:07.170
Now, I'm not saying you
should quit your job,

00:05:07.170 --> 00:05:08.420
even though that's what I did.

00:05:08.420 --> 00:05:11.090
I don't want to [INAUDIBLE]
to come here in a helicopter.

00:05:11.090 --> 00:05:13.270
I'm not saying quit your job.

00:05:13.270 --> 00:05:15.700
I'm saying I did because I
wanted to find out this answer

00:05:15.700 --> 00:05:18.520
and tell everyone else so
you guys didn't have to.

00:05:18.520 --> 00:05:20.300
That's what brings me here.

00:05:20.300 --> 00:05:22.750
I then went on a
globe trotting tour.

00:05:22.750 --> 00:05:25.990
I went to about 31
and change countries,

00:05:25.990 --> 00:05:28.450
just asking people on the
street, anyone I could

00:05:28.450 --> 00:05:32.110
who'd have a conversation
with me in English,

00:05:32.110 --> 00:05:34.640
what does it mean to be happy?

00:05:34.640 --> 00:05:36.330
And that's what brings me here.

00:05:36.330 --> 00:05:39.130
SPEAKER 1: So I want
to get into your method

00:05:39.130 --> 00:05:43.690
and what you prescribe in this
book, and your thoughts on how

00:05:43.690 --> 00:05:46.820
we can all achieve
our own happiness.

00:05:46.820 --> 00:05:49.310
Because we've hosted
other happiness experts,

00:05:49.310 --> 00:05:51.590
we've had Shawn Achor,
and [INAUDIBLE],,

00:05:51.590 --> 00:05:53.973
and of course,
Chade-Meng Tan, who

00:05:53.973 --> 00:05:55.390
created the Search
Inside Yourself

00:05:55.390 --> 00:05:58.510
program that many of our
own Googlers have attended.

00:05:58.510 --> 00:06:00.130
So talk to us
about your approach

00:06:00.130 --> 00:06:01.650
and what makes it unique.

00:06:01.650 --> 00:06:04.150
CHRIS BUTSCH: So my approach
to happiness completely changed

00:06:04.150 --> 00:06:07.715
by the time I reached
the Taj Mahal.

00:06:07.715 --> 00:06:09.590
I remember that day I
was in a terrible mood.

00:06:09.590 --> 00:06:10.990
And I couldn't figure out why.

00:06:10.990 --> 00:06:11.970
I was just crabby.

00:06:11.970 --> 00:06:13.360
And I was trying to
ruin everyone else's

00:06:13.360 --> 00:06:14.370
mood in my friend group.

00:06:14.370 --> 00:06:15.970
[LAUGHTER]

00:06:15.970 --> 00:06:18.550
So right, happiness
expert, right?

00:06:18.550 --> 00:06:21.310
So I go up to my
Australian friend, Helen.

00:06:21.310 --> 00:06:22.435
She sees the Taj.

00:06:22.435 --> 00:06:23.495
And she just lights up.

00:06:23.495 --> 00:06:25.078
She looks like a
little kid who's just

00:06:25.078 --> 00:06:26.410
discovered what Halloween is.

00:06:26.410 --> 00:06:27.778
She's, oh my God.

00:06:27.778 --> 00:06:28.320
Is that real?

00:06:28.320 --> 00:06:29.160
[LAUGHTER]

00:06:29.160 --> 00:06:32.360
Look at that accent.

00:06:32.360 --> 00:06:33.400
It is so special.

00:06:33.400 --> 00:06:36.400
I've never seen anything
like it in my life.

00:06:36.400 --> 00:06:38.260
And I go over to
her, and I'm, like,

00:06:38.260 --> 00:06:41.110
you know, he built
that for his dead wife?

00:06:41.110 --> 00:06:42.203
You know that, right?

00:06:42.203 --> 00:06:44.620
While he had other wives, and
they had to had to watch him

00:06:44.620 --> 00:06:46.675
build that.

00:06:46.675 --> 00:06:47.800
How do you think they felt?

00:06:47.800 --> 00:06:49.522
[LAUGHTER]

00:06:49.522 --> 00:06:51.230
And she turns-- yeah,
I'm speaking short.

00:06:51.230 --> 00:06:54.250
So she turns to me, and she's,
like, completely unfazed.

00:06:54.250 --> 00:06:56.070
She's, like, oh, come on, mate.

00:06:56.070 --> 00:06:58.637
I bet you 1,000 rupee
you're just in a bad mood

00:06:58.637 --> 00:06:59.720
because you're dehydrated.

00:06:59.720 --> 00:07:02.250
[LAUGHTER]

00:07:02.250 --> 00:07:04.060
What?

00:07:04.060 --> 00:07:06.160
So sure enough, I take
a huge swig of water,

00:07:06.160 --> 00:07:08.200
like I need to right now.

00:07:08.200 --> 00:07:11.870
And I feel instantly better.

00:07:11.870 --> 00:07:14.200
It just kills my bad mood.

00:07:14.200 --> 00:07:17.560
And she's like, eh,
isn't that better?

00:07:17.560 --> 00:07:19.250
And I keep getting
this feeling when

00:07:19.250 --> 00:07:21.190
I travel, it's, like,
Australians already know

00:07:21.190 --> 00:07:24.260
everything about happiness.

00:07:24.260 --> 00:07:26.260
They look at America and
they think we're, like,

00:07:26.260 --> 00:07:28.410
the muggles of happiness.

00:07:28.410 --> 00:07:30.020
It's a secret they
don't know yet.

00:07:30.020 --> 00:07:32.600
Give them some time.

00:07:32.600 --> 00:07:35.500
So after that moment,
when I realized

00:07:35.500 --> 00:07:37.450
that happiness can
be within our grasp

00:07:37.450 --> 00:07:40.783
if we just do a
few things right--

00:07:40.783 --> 00:07:42.200
up until that point
in my journey,

00:07:42.200 --> 00:07:44.820
I had let my inner hippie
make all the decisions.

00:07:44.820 --> 00:07:47.890
Yeah, man, you should,
like, go to a drum circle

00:07:47.890 --> 00:07:49.090
and it's really happiness.

00:07:49.090 --> 00:07:49.720
Yeah.

00:07:49.720 --> 00:07:54.520
But I fired that guy, and I
let my inner German take over.

00:07:54.520 --> 00:07:55.540
So that' my background.

00:07:55.540 --> 00:07:56.270
I'm German.

00:07:56.270 --> 00:07:58.013
It seems, like, place!

00:07:58.013 --> 00:08:01.100
[GERMAN ACCENT] We shall now
study this most efficient way

00:08:01.100 --> 00:08:01.600
to be happy.

00:08:01.600 --> 00:08:03.670
[LAUGHTER]

00:08:03.670 --> 00:08:04.300
Look at that.

00:08:04.300 --> 00:08:05.170
That's a Porsche.

00:08:05.170 --> 00:08:06.820
Porsche 911, it's a perfect car.

00:08:06.820 --> 00:08:08.260
This makes it perfect.

00:08:08.260 --> 00:08:09.780
Happiness formula.

00:08:09.780 --> 00:08:11.890
[INAUDIBLE]

00:08:11.890 --> 00:08:14.870
So that was when my whole
philosophy on happiness

00:08:14.870 --> 00:08:15.370
shifted.

00:08:15.370 --> 00:08:18.430
Instead of these ethereal
10,000 foot ideas,

00:08:18.430 --> 00:08:23.620
I wanted to find the short
term, instant happiness

00:08:23.620 --> 00:08:28.262
fixes, happiness hacks,
as I like to call it.

00:08:28.262 --> 00:08:30.220
SPEAKER 1: Let's go into
those happiness hacks.

00:08:30.220 --> 00:08:32.720
What are some of the ways that
we can increase our long term

00:08:32.720 --> 00:08:33.370
happiness?

00:08:33.370 --> 00:08:34.968
Will you call in
just a few minutes?

00:08:34.968 --> 00:08:35.760
CHRIS BUTSCH: Yeah.

00:08:35.760 --> 00:08:37.390
So there are two types of
happiness in the world.

00:08:37.390 --> 00:08:39.159
There's what I call
true happiness, which

00:08:39.159 --> 00:08:41.409
is the lasting,
nourishing happiness.

00:08:41.409 --> 00:08:44.460
And then there is pleasure,
which is the short term fix.

00:08:44.460 --> 00:08:45.580
Right?

00:08:45.580 --> 00:08:49.600
So my favorite form
of pleasure is a soda.

00:08:49.600 --> 00:08:53.500
And a soda will make you feel
good for about five minutes,

00:08:53.500 --> 00:08:56.775
followed by a pinch of regret.

00:08:56.775 --> 00:08:58.775
And it's not really-- you
can't build a lifetime

00:08:58.775 --> 00:09:02.870
with just drinking a
happy life drink, soda.

00:09:02.870 --> 00:09:06.060
Whereas true happiness is
a different form entirely.

00:09:06.060 --> 00:09:08.783
So true happiness is something
that you can do in the instant,

00:09:08.783 --> 00:09:10.450
but it will last and
have a slow burning

00:09:10.450 --> 00:09:12.260
effect on your happiness.

00:09:12.260 --> 00:09:19.005
So a challenge I had with
these instant happiness fixes,

00:09:19.005 --> 00:09:20.380
or the happiness
hacks, as I like

00:09:20.380 --> 00:09:22.345
to call them is that sometimes
I would prescribe one,

00:09:22.345 --> 00:09:23.845
and someone would
say, well, I don't

00:09:23.845 --> 00:09:25.840
feel like doing that
right now at all.

00:09:25.840 --> 00:09:29.340
Like, somebody had
a really bad day.

00:09:29.340 --> 00:09:30.670
Let's say here they do.

00:09:30.670 --> 00:09:31.400
You're exhausted.

00:09:31.400 --> 00:09:32.480
You're getting
home at 9 o'clock.

00:09:32.480 --> 00:09:32.980
Oh, my God.

00:09:32.980 --> 00:09:34.125
I'm just exhausted.

00:09:34.125 --> 00:09:35.500
I can't deal with
this right now.

00:09:35.500 --> 00:09:38.770
And your roommate
goes, just be grateful.

00:09:38.770 --> 00:09:40.130
You work at Google.

00:09:40.130 --> 00:09:41.060
Just be grateful.

00:09:41.060 --> 00:09:43.260
[LAUGHTER]

00:09:43.260 --> 00:09:43.760
Right.

00:09:43.760 --> 00:09:45.950
That doesn't make
you instantly happy.

00:09:45.950 --> 00:09:49.040
So I divided happiness
into two different levels.

00:09:49.040 --> 00:09:50.790
And these are all forms
of true happiness,

00:09:50.790 --> 00:09:51.760
as I like to call them.

00:09:51.760 --> 00:09:54.740
So level one is an
acronym I call MESH.

00:09:54.740 --> 00:09:56.590
MESH is the baseline
of things you

00:09:56.590 --> 00:10:00.100
need to do on a daily,
or every few days, basis

00:10:00.100 --> 00:10:03.460
to maintain kind of a
baseline concrete foundation

00:10:03.460 --> 00:10:04.600
of happiness.

00:10:04.600 --> 00:10:10.960
So MESH stands for meditation,
exercise, sleep, and hydration.

00:10:10.960 --> 00:10:12.520
So any time in my
journeys, or if I'm

00:10:12.520 --> 00:10:13.895
getting ready for
a speaking gig,

00:10:13.895 --> 00:10:17.770
and I just don't feel very
happy, and I can't pin

00:10:17.770 --> 00:10:20.950
point why that is,
I go and do my MESH.

00:10:20.950 --> 00:10:23.770
And I say, OK, I
meditated this morning.

00:10:23.770 --> 00:10:25.510
I exercised.

00:10:25.510 --> 00:10:27.400
I got five hours of
sleep last night--

00:10:27.400 --> 00:10:29.810
that's where I goofed up.

00:10:29.810 --> 00:10:32.180
And I found if I can
consistently do MESH

00:10:32.180 --> 00:10:35.320
throughout my life, I'll have
this higher level of baseline

00:10:35.320 --> 00:10:37.460
happiness, what positive
psychologists would

00:10:37.460 --> 00:10:39.590
call your hedonic setpoint.

00:10:39.590 --> 00:10:42.550
So just by doing MESH, you can
keep your hedonic set point

00:10:42.550 --> 00:10:44.870
a little higher than
it might be right now.

00:10:44.870 --> 00:10:47.830
So that's what I call the
level one of true happiness.

00:10:47.830 --> 00:10:50.200
Level two are the
more advanced stuff

00:10:50.200 --> 00:10:53.020
you can do once you have
your baseline taken care of.

00:10:53.020 --> 00:10:56.020
My acronym for
level two is GRIP.

00:10:56.020 --> 00:11:00.512
It's gratitude, relationships,
intellect, and passion.

00:11:00.512 --> 00:11:02.470
So once you have your
base needs taken care of,

00:11:02.470 --> 00:11:05.380
it's easier to be a
bit more grateful.

00:11:05.380 --> 00:11:12.357
So for me, for
gratitude, for example,

00:11:12.357 --> 00:11:13.940
when I was growing
up, as I mentioned,

00:11:13.940 --> 00:11:17.130
I kept saying things
like I'll be happy when.

00:11:17.130 --> 00:11:19.320
I'll be happy when I get
into Vanderbilt. When

00:11:19.320 --> 00:11:22.380
I work at Google I'll be happy.

00:11:22.380 --> 00:11:23.850
When I'm traveling
the world, I'm

00:11:23.850 --> 00:11:26.730
asking these people who
have staggering amounts

00:11:26.730 --> 00:11:28.560
of happiness--

00:11:28.560 --> 00:11:33.700
rickshaw drivers, janitors,
it's unbelievable.

00:11:33.700 --> 00:11:35.760
They started sentences
in different ways.

00:11:35.760 --> 00:11:38.790
Instead of I'll be happy
when, they started sentences

00:11:38.790 --> 00:11:42.240
with I'm happy because.

00:11:42.240 --> 00:11:47.420
I can never forget a rickshaw
driver I was riding with--

00:11:47.420 --> 00:11:49.890
actually, this is
a longer story,

00:11:49.890 --> 00:11:51.000
because he had a lot of--

00:11:51.000 --> 00:11:52.208
this guy had a lot of wisdom.

00:11:52.208 --> 00:11:53.660
So I've got a picture of him.

00:11:57.650 --> 00:11:58.560
That's me in Bhutan.

00:11:58.560 --> 00:12:00.602
Here, we'll just go through
my travel slide show.

00:12:00.602 --> 00:12:01.830
[LAUGHTER]

00:12:01.830 --> 00:12:03.960
That's me in Bhutan.

00:12:03.960 --> 00:12:05.400
That's India.

00:12:05.400 --> 00:12:08.430
That's off the side of
Buddha's first [INAUDIBLE]..

00:12:08.430 --> 00:12:11.100
I was meditating until
these Indian eighth graders

00:12:11.100 --> 00:12:12.750
came and surrounded me.

00:12:12.750 --> 00:12:15.120
[LAUGHTER]

00:12:15.120 --> 00:12:16.150
That's Sweden.

00:12:16.150 --> 00:12:19.590
So I was asked by the
Swedish to come to Sweden

00:12:19.590 --> 00:12:21.902
and teach them about happiness.

00:12:21.902 --> 00:12:23.610
For those of you who
don't know, Sweden's

00:12:23.610 --> 00:12:26.450
one of the happiest
countries in the world.

00:12:26.450 --> 00:12:30.240
So that's, like, Michael Phelps
asking for swimming lessons.

00:12:30.240 --> 00:12:32.602
I should go to Sweden, and
you all should teach me.

00:12:32.602 --> 00:12:37.230
Do a little bit of happiness
in both directions.

00:12:37.230 --> 00:12:37.950
Oh, yeah.

00:12:37.950 --> 00:12:41.540
So I visited a
Buddhist monastery.

00:12:41.540 --> 00:12:44.280
Just to learn mindfulness
meditation, I check into one.

00:12:44.280 --> 00:12:48.310
Turns out they run some Buddhist
monasteries just like Airbnbs.

00:12:48.310 --> 00:12:49.760
You just hit them up by email.

00:12:49.760 --> 00:12:52.240
And say, I'd like
to stay for 12 days.

00:12:52.240 --> 00:12:54.330
They might charge you
$40 a day, but that'll

00:12:54.330 --> 00:12:56.800
cover your meals and expenses.

00:12:56.800 --> 00:13:00.515
So I scheduled some time to
visit this Buddhist monastery

00:13:00.515 --> 00:13:01.140
in Mississippi.

00:13:01.140 --> 00:13:04.320
[LAUGHTER]

00:13:05.750 --> 00:13:08.630
Because when you
think the epicenter

00:13:08.630 --> 00:13:12.500
of Vietnamese Buddhist
thought, you go to Mississippi.

00:13:12.500 --> 00:13:18.060
So [INAUDIBLE]
and imagine you're

00:13:18.060 --> 00:13:20.993
about to walk into a
Buddhist monastery.

00:13:20.993 --> 00:13:22.410
What kind of things
would you see?

00:13:22.410 --> 00:13:23.950
What kind of things
would you smell?

00:13:23.950 --> 00:13:28.300
What would you expect
the monks to be doing?

00:13:28.300 --> 00:13:32.310
Maybe meditating, cleaning,
like dragging that rake

00:13:32.310 --> 00:13:34.500
through the sand or
whatever they do?

00:13:34.500 --> 00:13:38.104
None of that-- so I walk in, and
this monk hands me a margarita.

00:13:41.010 --> 00:13:44.220
I said, is this a margarita?

00:13:44.220 --> 00:13:45.420
He said, no.

00:13:45.420 --> 00:13:48.180
It's-- does anyone
have any guesses?

00:13:48.180 --> 00:13:51.780
It sounds like margarita,
but starts with a "B."

00:13:51.780 --> 00:13:54.000
If you can guess it, I'll
give you a free book.

00:13:54.000 --> 00:13:55.080
AUDIENCE: Beerita.

00:13:55.080 --> 00:13:58.620
CHRIS BUTSCH: Beerita,
no, not quite, we're

00:13:58.620 --> 00:14:00.092
at a Buddhist monastery--

00:14:00.092 --> 00:14:00.998
AUDIENCE: Buddharita?

00:14:00.998 --> 00:14:02.040
CHRIS BUTSCH: Buddharita!

00:14:02.040 --> 00:14:02.630
Yeah.

00:14:02.630 --> 00:14:04.728
So they hand me a Buddharita.

00:14:04.728 --> 00:14:05.270
So I walk in.

00:14:05.270 --> 00:14:06.932
It's a Buddharita.

00:14:06.932 --> 00:14:08.390
They're watching
a Bollywood movie,

00:14:08.390 --> 00:14:09.848
and they're doing
karaoke in there.

00:14:09.848 --> 00:14:12.390
[LAUGHTER]

00:14:12.390 --> 00:14:16.310
Turns out, even Vietnamese
devout Buddhist monks

00:14:16.310 --> 00:14:18.840
will take what they call a
lazy week, where they just

00:14:18.840 --> 00:14:21.311
have a staycation and hang out.

00:14:21.311 --> 00:14:24.030
So I showed up in the
middle of lazy week.

00:14:24.030 --> 00:14:26.250
And I'm doing--
within 20 minutes,

00:14:26.250 --> 00:14:30.622
I'm doing karaoke in a
language I don't speak.

00:14:30.622 --> 00:14:33.205
But later that week, I actually
learned mindfulness meditation

00:14:33.205 --> 00:14:35.670
and got back into
the rhythm of things.

00:14:35.670 --> 00:14:38.970
So after that long
diversion-- here we are.

00:14:38.970 --> 00:14:40.840
So that's Sati.

00:14:40.840 --> 00:14:42.270
Sati was the most
memorable person

00:14:42.270 --> 00:14:45.700
I spoke to in my entire
journey in 31 countries.

00:14:45.700 --> 00:14:51.290
I get in Sati's rickshaw, a
little outside the Taj Mahal.

00:14:51.290 --> 00:14:53.550
And I say, Sati, I'm a
student of happiness.

00:14:53.550 --> 00:14:57.320
I'm traveling the world to ask
people what happiness means.

00:14:57.320 --> 00:14:59.910
So what does
happiness mean to you?

00:14:59.910 --> 00:15:01.390
And he lights up.

00:15:01.390 --> 00:15:05.040
And he's instantly
got the answer.

00:15:05.040 --> 00:15:07.110
He goes, ah,
happiness, my friend.

00:15:07.110 --> 00:15:11.370
Happiness-- there are
two secrets to happiness.

00:15:11.370 --> 00:15:16.230
First, is that
happiness is love.

00:15:16.230 --> 00:15:20.640
Too many people in this world
wait around to receive love.

00:15:20.640 --> 00:15:26.750
What we forget as a species
is that we can give love.

00:15:26.750 --> 00:15:30.248
Sometimes in the middle of the
day, I still feel depressed.

00:15:30.248 --> 00:15:32.540
So what I'll do is I'll drive
down to the Mother Teresa

00:15:32.540 --> 00:15:34.300
house on the Ganges River.

00:15:34.300 --> 00:15:36.870
And I'll pour soup into the
mouths of those less fortunate

00:15:36.870 --> 00:15:37.850
than me.

00:15:37.850 --> 00:15:41.250
And I'll create love.

00:15:41.250 --> 00:15:42.780
And as long as I
can create love,

00:15:42.780 --> 00:15:46.360
I'll be the happiest
man in the world.

00:15:46.360 --> 00:15:49.780
I said, Sati, that's beautiful.

00:15:49.780 --> 00:15:51.780
But you said there are
two secrets to happiness.

00:15:51.780 --> 00:15:53.086
What's the other one?

00:15:53.086 --> 00:15:58.727
He said, ah, you need
to find a hot wife.

00:15:58.727 --> 00:16:01.529
[LAUGHTER]

00:16:04.010 --> 00:16:06.060
Sati, we were doing so well.

00:16:08.710 --> 00:16:10.320
So what else is there?

00:16:10.320 --> 00:16:13.290
So gratitude is also important.

00:16:13.290 --> 00:16:20.860
He said I'm happy because I
can feed my family tonight.

00:16:20.860 --> 00:16:24.090
I'm happy because I have a job.

00:16:24.090 --> 00:16:28.810
I'm happy because I have
unlimited love in my life.

00:16:28.810 --> 00:16:32.350
So very easy gratitude
hack is rather than

00:16:32.350 --> 00:16:34.570
start a sentence with
I'm grateful for, which

00:16:34.570 --> 00:16:39.370
for me personally doesn't really
work that well, I ask myself

00:16:39.370 --> 00:16:40.270
I'm happy because.

00:16:43.288 --> 00:16:44.580
And I'll answer that every day.

00:16:44.580 --> 00:16:46.440
It's OK if the answers
are the same every day.

00:16:46.440 --> 00:16:47.440
You've just got
to remind yourself

00:16:47.440 --> 00:16:48.865
why you're already happy.

00:16:48.865 --> 00:16:51.880
So instead of I'll
be happy when,

00:16:51.880 --> 00:16:54.910
and setting a goal for this
state you'll never reach--

00:16:54.910 --> 00:16:57.490
I'll be happy when,
I'll be happy when--

00:16:57.490 --> 00:16:59.650
remind yourself why
you're already happy.

00:16:59.650 --> 00:17:02.060
I'm happy because.

00:17:02.060 --> 00:17:05.260
SPEAKER 1: Let's talk about
the other part of that acronym.

00:17:05.260 --> 00:17:06.490
You mentioned relationships.

00:17:06.490 --> 00:17:08.530
Talk to us about how you
maintain relationships.

00:17:08.530 --> 00:17:10.569
I think a lot of folks,
you know, especially

00:17:10.569 --> 00:17:14.020
in the millennial crowd,
they've graduated from college

00:17:14.020 --> 00:17:16.730
in the last four or five years.

00:17:16.730 --> 00:17:19.790
They're now in their first
job, maybe mid to late 20s.

00:17:19.790 --> 00:17:23.180
And I think a lot of folks
find a sense of sadness,

00:17:23.180 --> 00:17:25.690
because a lot of the
relationships that they

00:17:25.690 --> 00:17:28.240
had when they were younger
start to fade away.

00:17:28.240 --> 00:17:29.490
People grow apart.

00:17:29.490 --> 00:17:29.990
Talk to me.

00:17:29.990 --> 00:17:31.840
Talk to us about
your relationships

00:17:31.840 --> 00:17:32.965
and how you maintain those.

00:17:32.965 --> 00:17:34.257
CHRIS BUTSCH: Yeah, absolutely.

00:17:34.257 --> 00:17:36.750
So this was definitely a day
when I was not traveling now.

00:17:36.750 --> 00:17:40.890
I was back home in Atlanta,
just me in front of a laptop

00:17:40.890 --> 00:17:43.690
doing happiness research,
like, full German.

00:17:43.690 --> 00:17:46.670
[GERMAN] find most efficient
way to be happy today.

00:17:46.670 --> 00:17:50.070
That was on my to do list,
find efficient happiness.

00:17:50.070 --> 00:17:51.480
So there was a
Ted talk about it.

00:17:51.480 --> 00:17:54.020
There was a study called
a Harvard Grant study.

00:17:54.020 --> 00:17:55.860
Has anyone heard of this before?

00:17:55.860 --> 00:17:56.860
Yeah, a couple of hands.

00:17:56.860 --> 00:17:58.960
The Harvard Grant study is--

00:17:58.960 --> 00:18:01.060
in the 1930s,
Harvard researchers

00:18:01.060 --> 00:18:04.030
decided to start collecting
millions of data points

00:18:04.030 --> 00:18:07.330
from hundreds of Bostonian
men, Harvard grads, or Harvard

00:18:07.330 --> 00:18:11.800
undergrads, but also men from
underprivileged neighborhoods.

00:18:11.800 --> 00:18:14.450
They didn't really have a
strong objective back then.

00:18:14.450 --> 00:18:16.220
They just wanted to
collect a ton of data

00:18:16.220 --> 00:18:20.800
that they could then
extrapolate ideas

00:18:20.800 --> 00:18:23.580
from later in the century.

00:18:23.580 --> 00:18:27.420
So in 2013, 75 years after
the inception of the study,

00:18:27.420 --> 00:18:30.130
a guy named Robert
Waldinger did a Ted talk

00:18:30.130 --> 00:18:34.330
revealing what they found
after 75 years, the number one

00:18:34.330 --> 00:18:37.540
indicator of a
happy, healthy life.

00:18:37.540 --> 00:18:41.260
Like, the one thing that kept
these guys happier and living

00:18:41.260 --> 00:18:44.720
longer and more successful
throughout their entire lives.

00:18:44.720 --> 00:18:47.450
And that one thing was
their relationships.

00:18:47.450 --> 00:18:50.380
And not the quantity of their
relationships, but the quality.

00:18:50.380 --> 00:18:53.820
So these guys-- one thing that
the happiest guys in the Grant

00:18:53.820 --> 00:18:58.655
study all had in common was
they had five close friends.

00:18:58.655 --> 00:19:00.280
And I took that idea
and I ran with it.

00:19:00.280 --> 00:19:02.050
And it turns out the
happiest societies

00:19:02.050 --> 00:19:06.380
in the world generally all
have some format of that five

00:19:06.380 --> 00:19:08.200
good friend rule.

00:19:08.200 --> 00:19:11.170
So Okinawa, for example--

00:19:11.170 --> 00:19:14.380
Okinawa is what they call a
blue zone, a UN designated

00:19:14.380 --> 00:19:18.520
area where they have a unique
amount of centenarians,

00:19:18.520 --> 00:19:20.380
people who live past 100.

00:19:20.380 --> 00:19:23.842
So sociologists around the
world love to study blue zones,

00:19:23.842 --> 00:19:26.050
because they can extrapolate
the secrets of long life

00:19:26.050 --> 00:19:27.710
and happiness.

00:19:27.710 --> 00:19:30.610
And one of the secrets of the
Okinawan society is that they

00:19:30.610 --> 00:19:35.610
what they call a moai, M-O-A-I.
I think that's right, M-O-A-I.

00:19:35.610 --> 00:19:39.170
So the moai is when
Okinawans are born,

00:19:39.170 --> 00:19:43.250
their families find them five
close friends that they'll have

00:19:43.250 --> 00:19:45.950
throughout their entire life.

00:19:45.950 --> 00:19:47.990
And you'll see
pictures of Okinawans

00:19:47.990 --> 00:19:54.610
with their moais over 100
years after they were created.

00:19:54.610 --> 00:19:57.910
I think, as a society,
we've lost touch

00:19:57.910 --> 00:19:59.980
of the quality of relationship.

00:19:59.980 --> 00:20:07.570
Because there are websites
that I will not name that

00:20:07.570 --> 00:20:11.890
tend to value
quantity over quality.

00:20:11.890 --> 00:20:15.557
When I hold back my
networking and trying

00:20:15.557 --> 00:20:17.140
to meet a million
people in the world,

00:20:17.140 --> 00:20:19.810
and instead pour my
resources into growing

00:20:19.810 --> 00:20:25.090
five chosen relationships,
my happiness skyrocketed.

00:20:25.090 --> 00:20:29.140
So that all being said, here
is a very simple tool for,

00:20:29.140 --> 00:20:31.150
as David said,
reconnecting with somebody.

00:20:31.150 --> 00:20:33.022
Maybe your best
friend in college

00:20:33.022 --> 00:20:34.480
who you haven't
spoken to in years.

00:20:38.910 --> 00:20:40.860
Facebook-- one thing
I love about Facebook

00:20:40.860 --> 00:20:43.500
is that it tells you when
your friends' birthdays are.

00:20:43.500 --> 00:20:47.250
The one thing I love to do
every day is call that person.

00:20:47.250 --> 00:20:49.500
I pick up the phone,
and I call them and just

00:20:49.500 --> 00:20:51.010
have a quick conversation.

00:20:51.010 --> 00:20:53.850
Sometimes I'll leave a voicemail
and I sing them happy birthday.

00:20:56.490 --> 00:21:01.350
But think about-- imagine
it's your birthday today.

00:21:01.350 --> 00:21:06.060
And 100 people write on your
Facebook wall, happy birthday.

00:21:06.060 --> 00:21:08.990
But one guy even
wrote HB on my wall.

00:21:08.990 --> 00:21:11.620
Wow, thanks.

00:21:11.620 --> 00:21:12.120
HB?

00:21:12.120 --> 00:21:15.390
I can tell you really put
a lot of thought into that.

00:21:15.390 --> 00:21:17.740
So on to HB, imagine
100 people wrote

00:21:17.740 --> 00:21:20.820
HB on your wall and one person
called you and wished you

00:21:20.820 --> 00:21:24.430
happy birthday and catch up.

00:21:24.430 --> 00:21:26.410
It makes so much difference.

00:21:26.410 --> 00:21:29.310
And what did that cost
you to pick up the phone?

00:21:29.310 --> 00:21:31.650
What did that cost to
them to make the call?

00:21:31.650 --> 00:21:36.840
Five minutes-- five minutes
to reignite a relationship.

00:21:36.840 --> 00:21:38.940
That's how I
reconnected with David.

00:21:38.940 --> 00:21:42.290
Probably I called you on your
birthday, or I just called you.

00:21:42.290 --> 00:21:46.170
And around that
time, and because I

00:21:46.170 --> 00:21:50.680
reignited a relationship that
I cared about, here I am.

00:21:50.680 --> 00:21:51.952
SPEAKER 1: Here we are.

00:21:51.952 --> 00:21:54.480
I think Myspace was
closed at the top eight.

00:21:54.480 --> 00:21:57.190
But I guess we're talking
the top five friends which

00:21:57.190 --> 00:21:58.628
we should consider.

