So we talked about gratitude.

00:23:55.210 --> 00:23:56.460
We talked about relationships.

00:23:56.460 --> 00:23:58.727
Talk to us about the
last two in the acronym.

00:23:58.727 --> 00:24:00.810
CHRIS BUTSCH: Yeah, intellect
and passions-- those

00:24:00.810 --> 00:24:03.550
are challenging ones.

00:24:03.550 --> 00:24:06.870
So for intellect,
what I like to do

00:24:06.870 --> 00:24:14.760
is set a Google alert
on my favorite topics.

00:24:14.760 --> 00:24:20.640
That might be happiness,
positive psychology.

00:24:20.640 --> 00:24:24.180
I also love cars, so Porsche.

00:24:24.180 --> 00:24:26.790
And I'll just, like, will you
email me the latest articles

00:24:26.790 --> 00:24:27.850
on those topics.

00:24:27.850 --> 00:24:31.750
And then all of a sudden, I've
got a pile of reading material

00:24:31.750 --> 00:24:34.950
for if I'm on the subway or
if I'm in an Uber or whatever.

00:24:34.950 --> 00:24:37.950
So I'm constantly
sharpening my intellect.

00:24:37.950 --> 00:24:40.290
Personally, I'm also
a big fan of the--

00:24:40.290 --> 00:24:43.320
I know they're a bit
controversial-- but the apps

00:24:43.320 --> 00:24:48.732
that you can play brain
training games on.

00:24:48.732 --> 00:24:50.190
They've been in
and out of the news

00:24:50.190 --> 00:24:51.990
because they've made some
marketing claims that

00:24:51.990 --> 00:24:53.060
may or may not have backing.

00:24:53.060 --> 00:24:54.893
But personally, I've
felt that they actually

00:24:54.893 --> 00:24:57.140
work and keep my brain sharp.

00:24:57.140 --> 00:24:59.190
And here's really
kind of a quirky one

00:24:59.190 --> 00:25:00.890
I've been doing lately.

00:25:00.890 --> 00:25:04.740
And I welcome your
judgmental stares.

00:25:04.740 --> 00:25:10.320
I was tutoring my neighbor's son
and getting him ready for SSAT.

00:25:10.320 --> 00:25:12.720
And he didn't have
the answer key around.

00:25:12.720 --> 00:25:16.620
So as an adult, I just had to
go through the SSAT practice

00:25:16.620 --> 00:25:19.530
questions and just
answer them myself.

00:25:19.530 --> 00:25:21.570
And I realized that
the questions designed

00:25:21.570 --> 00:25:23.988
to challenge elementary
and middle schoolers

00:25:23.988 --> 00:25:25.530
are actually pretty
good for jostling

00:25:25.530 --> 00:25:28.830
the parts of the brain, like
the prefrontal cortex, insular

00:25:28.830 --> 00:25:32.905
cortex, et cetera, for an
adult. So sometimes before a gig

00:25:32.905 --> 00:25:36.040
or if I'm just trying
to jog my creativity,

00:25:36.040 --> 00:25:39.180
I will download an SSAT
practice test off the internet

00:25:39.180 --> 00:25:42.290
and just take it.

00:25:42.290 --> 00:25:44.225
So that's intellect.

00:25:44.225 --> 00:25:46.100
Do three of those, and
you'll be the smartest

00:25:46.100 --> 00:25:48.020
person in the world.

00:25:48.020 --> 00:25:50.270
SPEAKER 1: Chris, you brought
your book with us today.

00:25:50.270 --> 00:25:54.920
Talk to us about the experience
of publishing your own book.

00:25:54.920 --> 00:25:57.330
And what folks who
read it can expect

00:25:57.330 --> 00:25:58.978
to get out from reading that.

00:25:58.978 --> 00:25:59.770
CHRIS BUTSCH: Sure.

00:25:59.770 --> 00:26:04.570
So I drafted the book
in Microsoft Word.

00:26:04.570 --> 00:26:06.970
And I just had it
sitting in this document

00:26:06.970 --> 00:26:10.360
and wondered what are
my next options, right?

00:26:10.360 --> 00:26:11.875
Traditionally, you
can self publish.

00:26:11.875 --> 00:26:14.680
It means you send it
to Amazon or whoever.

00:26:14.680 --> 00:26:18.770
And they'll send you back
your book and books in a box.

00:26:18.770 --> 00:26:21.220
You can go for traditional
publishing, where you get

00:26:21.220 --> 00:26:23.590
an agent, then pitch it around.

00:26:23.590 --> 00:26:27.130
And you might get a bite at
a major or a small publishing

00:26:27.130 --> 00:26:27.630
house.

00:26:27.630 --> 00:26:30.310
And they may or may not
take some creative control.

00:26:30.310 --> 00:26:33.420
That might be three
months, or three years.

00:26:33.420 --> 00:26:38.970
And I thought, I don't like
the idea of self-publishing.

00:26:38.970 --> 00:26:41.290
That doesn't feel
really like I'd

00:26:41.290 --> 00:26:44.230
be joining the industry
if I just self-published.

00:26:44.230 --> 00:26:46.810
I also don't feel like I want
to lose any creative control.

00:26:46.810 --> 00:26:48.352
So there is a third
option now called

00:26:48.352 --> 00:26:51.270
hybrid publishing, where you
work with a boutique publisher.

00:26:51.270 --> 00:26:53.020
But if you pay some
of the costs up front,

00:26:53.020 --> 00:26:57.280
they'll let you retain higher
royalties and creative control.

00:26:57.280 --> 00:27:00.160
That's exactly what I did with
a small company called BookLogix

00:27:00.160 --> 00:27:02.240
in Alpharetta, Georgia.

00:27:02.240 --> 00:27:04.510
So they are my formal publisher.

00:27:04.510 --> 00:27:07.690
That's my publisher, the
little B on the book.

00:27:07.690 --> 00:27:10.230
What that let me do is
retain creative control.

00:27:10.230 --> 00:27:14.680
And we went from books
sitting in a Word document

00:27:14.680 --> 00:27:20.770
to edited critiques and
books in hand, in about four,

00:27:20.770 --> 00:27:22.180
five months.

00:27:22.180 --> 00:27:24.243
And that can be
pretty intensive.

00:27:24.243 --> 00:27:25.660
I don't know if
you work full-time

00:27:25.660 --> 00:27:28.620
at Google, if you'll have time
to do that in four months.

00:27:28.620 --> 00:27:29.800
But know that it's possible.

00:27:29.800 --> 00:27:31.870
If you have a book hanging
around in your head,

00:27:31.870 --> 00:27:34.690
know that it's never
been easier to publish

00:27:34.690 --> 00:27:37.720
your own work, your own book.

00:27:37.720 --> 00:27:41.400
So, after that, I
wanted to galvanize

00:27:41.400 --> 00:27:44.970
all my friends and family
into supporting the book.

00:27:44.970 --> 00:27:47.860
The traditional school of
thought is to launch on Amazon.

00:27:47.860 --> 00:27:50.740
But I wanted to do something
a bit more fun and gamified.

00:27:50.740 --> 00:27:53.220
So I ran a Kickstarter
campaign to fund

00:27:53.220 --> 00:27:56.690
the book, and all of my
upfront self-publishing costs.

00:27:56.690 --> 00:27:59.500
So the thing I love
about Kickstarter

00:27:59.500 --> 00:28:02.560
is you get a ping on your phone
every time somebody donates.

00:28:02.560 --> 00:28:06.310
So I was connecting with some of
my old teachers, my old English

00:28:06.310 --> 00:28:07.820
High School teacher.

00:28:07.820 --> 00:28:09.670
Yeah, I'm running
this online fundraiser

00:28:09.670 --> 00:28:11.430
to publish my first book.

00:28:11.430 --> 00:28:13.760
Oh, that sounds pretty cool.

00:28:13.760 --> 00:28:16.040
I get back to my car and
I get a ping on my phone.

00:28:16.040 --> 00:28:20.440
Mrs. Finch donated $120
to your Kickstarter.

00:28:20.440 --> 00:28:23.050
And that's an isolated case.

00:28:23.050 --> 00:28:25.695
But if you run your own
Kickstarter campaign,

00:28:25.695 --> 00:28:27.070
or whichever
fundraising platform

00:28:27.070 --> 00:28:32.110
you choose, and you put your own
creative creation on the line,

00:28:32.110 --> 00:28:34.590
and you see people
from your past life,

00:28:34.590 --> 00:28:38.470
and your current boss, your
best friend, his best friend,

00:28:38.470 --> 00:28:41.595
pouring money to help you give
birth to something that you

00:28:41.595 --> 00:28:42.970
care about,
something that you've

00:28:42.970 --> 00:28:44.610
put your heart and soul into--

00:28:44.610 --> 00:28:46.610
it was the most amazing,
humbling experience

00:28:46.610 --> 00:28:48.520
of my entire life.

00:28:48.520 --> 00:28:50.480
And from a German
perspective, it

00:28:50.480 --> 00:28:53.010
helped me pre-sell
my first 500 copies.

00:28:53.010 --> 00:28:54.600
[LAUGHTER]

00:28:54.600 --> 00:28:56.020
[INAUDIBLE]

00:28:56.513 --> 00:28:58.930
SPEAKER 1: We're headed to
what's in the book in a second,

00:28:58.930 --> 00:29:00.130
but we've got a live
question right here.

00:29:00.130 --> 00:29:00.713
Go to that.

00:29:00.713 --> 00:29:01.480
CHRIS BUTSCH: Yes, sir.

00:29:01.480 --> 00:29:02.313
AUDIENCE: Yeah, man.

00:29:02.313 --> 00:29:03.640
Thanks for coming.

00:29:03.640 --> 00:29:06.940
So I've seen some
research that suggests

00:29:06.940 --> 00:29:11.703
that most of each
person's happiness level

00:29:11.703 --> 00:29:13.120
is predetermined
by their genetics

00:29:13.120 --> 00:29:15.280
and there's only a little
bit that we can affect.

00:29:15.280 --> 00:29:16.450
Do you think that's true?

00:29:16.450 --> 00:29:17.908
Like, what do you
think about that?

00:29:17.908 --> 00:29:18.700
CHRIS BUTSCH: Yeah.

00:29:18.700 --> 00:29:20.956
If I can remember the numbers
off the top of my head,

00:29:20.956 --> 00:29:24.190
I wonder if it was
[INAUDIBLE] work.

00:29:24.190 --> 00:29:27.070
I think it was 50% is genetic.

00:29:27.070 --> 00:29:31.280
10% is controlled by factors
outside of your control--

00:29:31.280 --> 00:29:33.200
the weather, the
stocks, et cetera.

00:29:33.200 --> 00:29:36.700
And they say 40% is completely
within your control.

00:29:36.700 --> 00:29:37.900
So 40% is a lot.

00:29:37.900 --> 00:29:40.060
That's the difference
between a D minus and an A

00:29:40.060 --> 00:29:41.860
plus in happiness.

00:29:41.860 --> 00:29:47.770
So the challenge is, as it
goes with a lot of happiness

00:29:47.770 --> 00:29:49.870
research, happiness
is very subjective.

00:29:49.870 --> 00:29:56.350
It's difficult to measure
happiness in objective terms.

00:29:56.350 --> 00:30:00.610
You can't really
quantify exactly

00:30:00.610 --> 00:30:03.100
how happy glad people make
you, because you can't just

00:30:03.100 --> 00:30:06.010
show up in a [INAUDIBLE]
with an MRI machine.

00:30:06.010 --> 00:30:09.010
You just throw people in it,
and measure the difference.

00:30:09.010 --> 00:30:10.660
That being said,
they have measured

00:30:10.660 --> 00:30:13.720
our longitudinal
effects of meditation.

00:30:13.720 --> 00:30:17.250
And I think, more subjectively,
the self-reported effects

00:30:17.250 --> 00:30:18.700
of [INAUDIBLE], et cetera.

00:30:18.700 --> 00:30:21.260
So to expand on your question.

00:30:21.260 --> 00:30:23.500
Do I believe in
the 50-40-10 rule,

00:30:23.500 --> 00:30:28.420
or do I believe in some of this
more subjective or open-ended

00:30:28.420 --> 00:30:30.220
happiness research?

00:30:30.220 --> 00:30:32.220
I can't find any
counter evidence to it.

00:30:32.220 --> 00:30:38.590
I haven't really found work by
Chade-Meng Tan, or Shawn Achor,

00:30:38.590 --> 00:30:42.700
or Sonya Lyubomirsky
that I disagree with.

00:30:42.700 --> 00:30:45.592
I've found subjective
evidence in my own life.

00:30:45.592 --> 00:30:46.300
AUDIENCE: Thanks.

00:30:46.300 --> 00:30:46.985
CHRIS BUTSCH: Thank you.

00:30:46.985 --> 00:30:48.890
SPEAKER 1: We've got
another live question.

00:30:48.890 --> 00:30:49.432
AUDIENCE: Hi.

00:30:49.432 --> 00:30:50.390
This is taller than me.

00:30:50.390 --> 00:30:51.830
Thanks for being here.

00:30:51.830 --> 00:30:53.940
I think this topic is
definitely [INAUDIBLE]..

00:30:53.940 --> 00:30:55.590
We've all seen at
least the headline

00:30:55.590 --> 00:30:58.880
of the [INAUDIBLE] millennial
burnout article and things

00:30:58.880 --> 00:30:59.380
like that.

00:30:59.380 --> 00:31:01.380
So I was wondering,
from your perspective,

00:31:01.380 --> 00:31:03.340
why did you need
to be number one?

00:31:03.340 --> 00:31:04.890
I know that makes this
question, like, hard to answer.

00:31:04.890 --> 00:31:07.260
And what about being millennial,
[INAUDIBLE] question,

00:31:07.260 --> 00:31:10.490
and, on the flip side, like, how
does being a millennial informs

00:31:10.490 --> 00:31:11.933
the solution [INAUDIBLE]?

00:31:11.933 --> 00:31:13.600
CHRIS BUTSCH: Thank
you for asking that.

00:31:13.600 --> 00:31:14.100
It's funny.

00:31:14.100 --> 00:31:16.960
The number one feedback I get
on the book is, it's great.

00:31:16.960 --> 00:31:19.540
Why is millennial the title?

00:31:19.540 --> 00:31:22.835
One of my family friends,
their daughter read the book.

00:31:22.835 --> 00:31:24.460
And then, when she
went off to college,

00:31:24.460 --> 00:31:26.870
she couldn't find
her copy of the book.

00:31:26.870 --> 00:31:29.550
That was because her mother
had stolen it and hidden it

00:31:29.550 --> 00:31:33.280
in her room because
she wanted to read it.

00:31:33.280 --> 00:31:35.962
And anyone over 35
will read the book

00:31:35.962 --> 00:31:37.170
and ask me the same question.

00:31:37.170 --> 00:31:40.073
Why are you orienting
this just to millennials?

00:31:40.073 --> 00:31:42.240
And to be honest, I don't
really have a good answer.

00:31:42.240 --> 00:31:44.407
I've actually been thinking
about retitling the book

00:31:44.407 --> 00:31:46.867
to just making happiness.

00:31:46.867 --> 00:31:48.950
Because I do want to appeal
to a broader audience.

00:31:48.950 --> 00:31:52.210
I think this positive
psychology, these happiness

00:31:52.210 --> 00:31:55.480
hacks, this knowledge
of how our brain works

00:31:55.480 --> 00:31:57.940
and how to improve
our lifestyles

00:31:57.940 --> 00:32:00.220
applies to every generation.

00:32:00.220 --> 00:32:02.140
I just wanted to
galvanize millennials

00:32:02.140 --> 00:32:04.270
into taking advantage
of it because I

00:32:04.270 --> 00:32:06.730
feel that we're poised to make
the most change in the world

00:32:06.730 --> 00:32:08.530
right now that we
desperately need.

00:32:11.980 --> 00:32:20.253
I think the challenges specific
to the millennial audience

00:32:20.253 --> 00:32:21.170
that we grew up with--

00:32:21.170 --> 00:32:26.360
I'm 28-- is social
media, I think,

00:32:26.360 --> 00:32:29.820
has made the most impact.

00:32:29.820 --> 00:32:31.440
I think social
media was originally

00:32:31.440 --> 00:32:35.910
conceived, business objectives
aside, to bring us together

00:32:35.910 --> 00:32:37.540
as a society.

00:32:37.540 --> 00:32:40.440
So if you can catalyze the
way that people communicate

00:32:40.440 --> 00:32:46.110
and make a fence, that should
be great for humankind, right?

00:32:46.110 --> 00:32:49.380
But I think what we've done is
use that not as a supplement

00:32:49.380 --> 00:32:50.920
or a catalyst in
social behavior,

00:32:50.920 --> 00:32:54.150
but as a replacement, right?

00:32:54.150 --> 00:32:57.430
So why would I call
up a friend if I

00:32:57.430 --> 00:32:59.400
can just Facebook chat him?

00:32:59.400 --> 00:33:04.050
Why would I try to
connect with this person

00:33:04.050 --> 00:33:07.020
again over coffee, if I can just
connect with them on Facebook

00:33:07.020 --> 00:33:10.030
at friend whatever.

00:33:10.030 --> 00:33:15.330
So I think what
also goes with that

00:33:15.330 --> 00:33:19.050
is a phenomenon they call
impressions management.

00:33:19.050 --> 00:33:22.080
So as a species, we've evolved.

00:33:22.080 --> 00:33:24.920
We are the offspring of
the smartest, most powerful

00:33:24.920 --> 00:33:26.460
among our species.

00:33:26.460 --> 00:33:28.980
And the way that we've
shown that off in the past

00:33:28.980 --> 00:33:30.490
is by what they
called peacocking.

00:33:30.490 --> 00:33:30.990
Right?

00:33:30.990 --> 00:33:34.650
So making ourselves look smart,
intelligent, and impressive

00:33:34.650 --> 00:33:38.430
to the small audience
that's around us.

00:33:38.430 --> 00:33:41.130
What Facebook, Instagram, and
social media sites have given

00:33:41.130 --> 00:33:42.890
us is a microzone.

00:33:42.890 --> 00:33:45.480
So instead of peacocking
to just five people

00:33:45.480 --> 00:33:47.010
that we might care
about, we're now

00:33:47.010 --> 00:33:51.070
trying to peacock to 1,500
people on a daily basis.

00:33:51.070 --> 00:33:54.520
That's a staggering amount of
pressure to put on ourselves.

00:33:54.520 --> 00:33:59.400
I remember back in college, I
had two friends, Ann and Dave.

00:33:59.400 --> 00:34:01.750
They were that couple that
dated throughout college.

00:34:01.750 --> 00:34:03.833
Everyone thought, oh,
they're that perfect couple.

00:34:03.833 --> 00:34:05.555
We need to be like Ann and Dave.

00:34:05.555 --> 00:34:06.930
Well, I knew Ann
and Dave better.

00:34:06.930 --> 00:34:09.880
[LAUGHTER]

00:34:09.880 --> 00:34:10.949
Yeah.

00:34:10.949 --> 00:34:13.290
I knew-- and these are
not their real names,

00:34:13.290 --> 00:34:15.429
but they know who they are.

00:34:15.429 --> 00:34:21.659
So one night, I was talking
to Ann, and Dave came in.

00:34:21.659 --> 00:34:25.020
And he demanded to know
who she was on the phone

00:34:25.020 --> 00:34:27.389
with earlier that day.

00:34:27.389 --> 00:34:29.377
Who does that?

00:34:29.377 --> 00:34:31.460
Who were you on the phone
call with earlier today?

00:34:31.460 --> 00:34:32.877
She's like, none
of your business.

00:34:32.877 --> 00:34:33.900
She's the jealous type.

00:34:33.900 --> 00:34:35.400
He's holding a pizza.

00:34:35.400 --> 00:34:38.965
And he takes the pizza out and
throws it against the wall.

00:34:38.965 --> 00:34:42.230
I'm, like, this is
not a perfect couple.

00:34:42.230 --> 00:34:43.659
And yet everyone
thinks they are,

00:34:43.659 --> 00:34:45.750
because they post beautiful
pictures on Facebook

00:34:45.750 --> 00:34:46.840
all the time.

00:34:46.840 --> 00:34:48.929
How many couples are out
there judging themselves

00:34:48.929 --> 00:34:52.659
against the couples that are
on Facebook that look perfect.

00:34:52.659 --> 00:34:54.870
And everyone looks
perfect, because you're all

00:34:54.870 --> 00:34:57.390
taking beautiful pictures in
front of the Eiffel Tower,

00:34:57.390 --> 00:35:00.450
her legs popping.

00:35:00.450 --> 00:35:02.700
But that's just not real life.

00:35:02.700 --> 00:35:06.420
So I think because
we all spend so much

00:35:06.420 --> 00:35:10.500
time in this arena that's not
reflective of the humdrumness

00:35:10.500 --> 00:35:13.950
and the challenges of real life,
we have higher expectations

00:35:13.950 --> 00:35:16.170
for each of ourselves.

00:35:16.170 --> 00:35:19.240
And it's OK to remind ourselves
that we're all just human.

00:35:19.240 --> 00:35:23.130
And the best reminder
that we're all human

00:35:23.130 --> 00:35:26.780
is to spend time
with other humans.

